BUCKEYE ROT AND BACTERIAL LEAF BLIGHT, TOMATO - INDIA: (HIMACHAL PRADESH)
*************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Sun 26 Sep 2010
Source: Sindh Today News, Indo Asian News Service (IANS) report [edited]
<http://www.sindhtoday.net/news/2/179284.htm>


Incessant rains have destroyed 60-70 percent of the tomato crop in
Himachal Pradesh pushing up prices in north Indian cities. Himachal
Pradesh is a major tomato-producing state of the region.

"The crop in Solan, Shimla, Mandi, Sirmaur, Bilaspur, and Kullu
[districts] was damaged due to excess rainfall," Agriculture Joint
Director RK Saroya said. "There is hardly any healthy crop to reach
the market."

A tomato farmer near Solan town said, "In August [2010] the crop
damage percentage was 30-40 percent. In September it rose up to 70
percent. The excessive rains also took a toll on other vegetable crops
including cabbage, capsicum, and beans."

The vegetable production this 2010 season is likely to be 550 000
tonnes against the expected target of 650 000 tonnes. An official of
the agriculture department said most of the remaining crop in the
state was hit by the fungus disease buckeye rot and bacteria-caused
leaf spot.

[Byline: Vishal Gulati]

